[Student "S"]
{You show your 4-card Major. Bid 1\S. Partner rebids 2\C. What do you say next? 

You have a nice \D suit but don't bid it now. That would be FSF and partner would assume you didn't have a \D stopper. 

With 13 points, bid what you expect to make, 3NT. Partner passes.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:7.KQ863.T4.AKT86 QJ.JT7.J6532.753 AK985.A5.87.QJ94 T6432.942.AKQ9.2"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "5C"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1H pass 1S pass 2C pass 2D pass 3C pass 5C all pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "333935c04299af90f8c22cd36eddfbd740e98f9a339693655f489735b9b38b5e"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/fourth_suit_forcing"]
[Student "S"]
{You open 1\H. As expected, partner responds 1\S.  

This is easy bidding so far. You bid your second 5-card suit, 2\C.

Partner says 2\D.  

Partner's bid is FSF. He wants to know if you have 3 \Ss, (you don't), or if you can stop \Ds, (you can't). So you have to rebid one of your 5-carders, and you should bid the lower-ranking one. You bid 3\C and partner raises to 5\C.}

